<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRO FOOTBALL DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE NFL; PANTHERS TOLD NOT TO TALK WITH 
CAPERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue on Friday ordered the expansion Carolina 
Panthers to end discussions with Pittsburgh defensive coordinator Dom Capers 
regarding possible employment with the team. 
</P>
<P>
 Capers and fired Philadelphia coach Rich Kotite have emerged as the top 
candidates for the Carolina coaching job.The Panthers previously failed to 
convince former Washington coach Joe Gibbs to take the job. 
</P>
<P>
 Tagliabue sent a letter to Panther owner Jerry Richardson, summoning team 
officials to a hearing in New York next week to review reports that the club 
has violated anti-tampering policies. 
</P>
<P>
 The NFL has longstanding rules prohibiting discussions between a team and 
coaches working for another team under an ongoing contract. The rules bar such 
discussions with assistant coaches or coordinators until their teams finish 
their seasons. The Steelers are involved in the NFL playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Nick Nicolau was fired as offensive coordinator of the Indianapolis Colts. 
</P>
<P>
 "We felt a change was necessary," said Bill Tobin, Colt vice president of 
football operations. 
</P>
<P>
 Nicolau, 61, came to the Colts in 1992 with Coach Ted Marchibroda from the 
Buffalo Bills, where he was the receivers coach. Before that, he was the 
receivers coach for the Raiders. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Dallas Cowboy running back Emmitt Smith is spending this week doing 
conditioning work and avoiding taking hits on his injured left hamstring. He 
said his leg is "feeling OK -- it's definitely not ready, though." . . . Former 
Green Bay Packer fullback Dexter McNabb signed a free-agent contract with the 
expansion Jacksonville Jaguars. Terms were not disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
