<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALVIN AILEY DANCE THEATER SCHEDULES LENGTHY VISIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater returns to Southern California in 
February for the longest visit in its history.  
</P>
<P>
 Three engagements are scheduled: Feb. 17-26 at the Wiltern Theatre (sponsored 
by UCLA), Feb. 28 and March 1 at the McCallum Theatre in Palm Desert, and March 
2-5 at the Cerritos Center for the Performing Arts.The company last appeared 
locally in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 Judith Jamison's fifth season as company artistic director is dedicated to the 
late Lula E. Cooper (Ailey's mother) and features female choreographers. New 
works by Elisa Monte ("Mnemonic Verses") and Brenda Way ("Scissors, Paper, 
Stone") have been announced for the Southland tour, along with Jamison's 
"Hymn," which features a text by actress-playwright Anna Deavere Smith. A new 
production of Ulysses Dove's "Vespers" (1986) will also be danced in Los 
Angeles and Cerritos. 
</P>
<P>
 Below, the repertory: 
</P>
<P>
 Wiltern Theatre 
</P>
<P>
 Feb. 17, 8 p.m.; Feb. 23, 8 p.m.; Feb. 24, 8 p.m.: "Hymn" 
(Jamison/Ruggieri/Deavere Smith), "Vespers" (Dove/Rouse), "Revelations" 
(Ailey/traditional spirituals). 
</P>
<P>
 Feb. 18, 2 and 8 p.m.; Feb. 26, 2 p.m.: "Carmina Burana" (Butler/Orff), 
"Treading" (Monte/Reich), "Revelations." 
</P>
<P>
 Feb. 19, 2 and 8 p.m.; Feb. 25, 2 and 8 p.m.: "Night Creature" 
(Ailey/Ellington), "Scissors, Paper Stone" (Way/blues and rock recordings), 
"Masekela Langage" (Ailey/Masekela), "The Winter in Lisbon" (Wilson/Gillespie). 
</P>
<P>
 McCallum Theatre 
</P>
<P>
 Feb. 28, 8 p.m.: "The River" (Ailey/Ellington), "The Winter in Lisbon," 
"Revelations." 
</P>
<P>
 March 1, 11 a.m.: (special free invitational student performance). 
</P>
<P>
 Cerritos Center 
</P>
<P>
 March 2, 8 p.m.: "Night Creature," "Treading," "Shelter" (Zollar/Wedderburn), 
"Revelations." 
</P>
<P>
 March 3, 8 p.m.: "The River," "Hymn," "Revelations." 
</P>
<P>
 March 4, 2 p.m.: "The River," "Mnemonic Verses" (Monte/Hassell), "The Winter 
in Lisbon." 
</P>
<P>
 March 4, 8 p.m.: "Carmina Burana," "Scissors, Paper, Stone," "Revelations." 
</P>
<P>
 March 5, 8 p.m.: "Night Creature," "Treading," "Vespers," "Revelations." 
</P>
