<HEADLINE>
<P>
DOG'S ACTION SPARKS HOME BLAZE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It wasn't as bad as the time Mrs. O'Leary's cow kicked over the lantern and 
started the Great Chicago Fire, but a large Valley puppy nonetheless created a 
stir Friday when its antics ignited a small home fire. No one, including the 
dog, was injured. 
</P>
<P>
 The puppy's owners had installed a movable "doggy door" in their sliding door 
so the dog could go in and out of the house, said Brian Humphrey, spokesman for 
the Los Angeles Fire Department. 
</P>
<P>
 But shortly after 5 p.m., the puppy knocked the dog door over and onto a floor 
furnace, which ignited the plastic unit, Humphrey said. The fire, which caused 
about $7,000 in damage, then spread to a nearby closet. 
</P>
<P>
 It took 15 firefighters about 20 minutes to put out the fire in the 4400 block 
of Laurelgrove Avenue, Humphrey said. 
</P>
<P>
 The cause of the blaze was listed as "a harlequin Great Dane puppy," Humphrey 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
